The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, April 24, 2004 				 Samsung eyes 50% revenue from mobiles
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT				 	 Samsung CEO K. S. Kim in Delhi on Friday. Picture by Jagdish Yadav																								New Delhi, April 23: Samsung India Electronics Ltd hopes to generate 50 per cent of its revenue from mobile phone sales during the next financial year.																								The company today launched the first bar mobile phone with a rotating camera and an integrated flash. The latest model  SGH X600  is priced at Rs 14,599 and offers a multi language display in Hindi, Tamil and Marathi and will soon include other languages. The price for the models in this range starts from Rs 8,699.																								Samsung expects the colour camera phones to fuel growth of its mobile phones. Moreover, reductions in duty will also push sales of mobile phones.																								K. S. Kim, president and CEO of Samsungs South West Asia regional headquarters, said, We expect the colour camera phone segment to grow significantly this year. The segment will contribute about 30 per cent of our total revenues. By the middle of this year it would go up to 50 per cent. 																								The company has launched 12 mobile phone models in India and will double this number during the year. Samsung will focus both on sale of mobile phones based on both global system for mobile communications (GSM) and code division multiple access (CDMA) technologies.																								On the GSM front, we have finalised tie-ups with AirTel, Idea and Oasis for sale of our mobile phones of different models with their tariff packages. It will also include the camera phones. While we already have an agreement with Reliance Infocomm for sale of camera phones and other models based on CDMA technologies, said Kunal Ahooja, vice-president Telecom Samsung India. 
